<HEAD>Small Plane Makes Emergency Landing During Storm, Four Killed, Officials
Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A small commercial plane with 20 people aboard made an emergency landing near the Venezuelan border during a storm Sunday, killing four people and injuring 12, the government said. The plane, a Canadian-built Twin Otter operated by the private domestic company <PERSON> Aerotaca </PERSON>, landed on a bank of the <LOCATION> Casanara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> because of a driving rain, said <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The report did not say what damage the plane suffered or how the four people died, and it did not give the breakdown of passengers and crew. A press report said all people aboard the twin-engine plane were Colombian. Among the passengers were Colombian folk singer and composer <PERSON> Arnulfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Briceno </PERSON> as well as reporters and television cameramen invited by the state-owned company <ORGANIZATION> Ecopetrol </ORGANIZATION> to retrace the route taken by <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolivar </PERSON> during the final battles on Colombian independence from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> 170 years ago, said an agency spokesman. The names of the other passengers and crew were were not immediately available and it was not known whether <PERSON> Briceno </PERSON> was among the victims. The plane was flying between <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> and Tame, an oil town 220 miles east of the capital, the spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity. A company source said the pilot reported the plane could not land in Tame because of the heavy rain and was fly on to <LOCATION> Bucaramang </LOCATION>, the largest city in eastern <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. Authorities declared the plane missing when it failed to reach its destination. Some Colombian <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> units searched for the plane, but it was not immediately clear who spo