<HEAD>Seven Overcome by Carbon Monoxide at Ice Rink Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEAVERTON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven people hospitalized after being overcome by carbon monoxide in an ice skating rink were released Saturday, and special precautions were taken to avoid more problems. The seven were among 25 people sickened by gas emitted from an ice grooming machine, known as a Zamboni, during a hockey tournament at the rink Friday. The others were treated with oxygen at the scene. A faulty exhaust system on the Zamboni apparently caused it to emit the carbon monoxide, which stayed close to the ice, said <ORGANIZATION> Tualatin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> dispatcher <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Nodland </PERSON>. He said the carbon monoxide readings in the arena were at safe levels Saturday. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McBride </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arena </ORGANIZATION> general manager, said large fans were set up Saturday to circulate air at the rink and the ice grooming machine was fitted with a catalytic converter to reduce its emissions. He theorized that extra refrigeration used to keep the ice solid in recent warm weather brought the temperature so low in the arena Friday that carbon monoxide from the Zamboni stayed near the ice and would n't disperse normally. This was the second year in a row that carbon monoxide poisoning has occurred at the rink during a hockey game for the Rose Festival, the city's annual June festival. Paramedics were first alerted to the problems at the rink Friday night when a parent sought aid for a child that was vomiting. Several children complained of dizziness and nausea, and at least one child fainted. Dr. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorts </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Providence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> said one boy brought there Friday night was treated for 90 minutes in a glass-enclosed, pressurized chamber, where pure oxygen was pumped into the boy's lungs Because of the relatively low levels of the carbon monoxide in Friday's incident, <PERSON> Lorts </PERSON> said, it is unlikely that any person at the rink would suffer long-term ill effects. Carbon monoxide is odorless, tasteless and colorless and is produced during combustion. Capt. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kline </PERSON>, who headed <ORGANIZATION> Tualatin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION>'s hazardous-materials team at the rink, said initial readings of carbon monoxide in the building were 120 to 170 parts per million of air He said 50 parts per million was considered the maximum concentration before people felt sick, and 1,500 parts per million would be lethal.
</TEXT>
