<FIRST>r a AM-HalfMoon     06-11 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Half Moon,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Replica Of Henry Hudson's Ship Christened At Albany Dock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GERMAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly four centuries after explorer <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>'s crew mutinied and set him adrift, a replica of his ship has been launched to honor the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>' contributions to the New World. `` What the sea separates, the shipbuilder unites,'' ship designer <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> told a crowd of about 500 Saturday before the christening of the Half Moon. The 85-foot, 120-ton wooden vessel was lowered by crane into the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> discovered in 1609 during his search for a <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> passage to the Orient. Two years later, <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>'s crew mutinied, setting him, his young son and seven others adrift in a small boat in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. They were never seen again. The replica was conceived by <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendricks </PERSON>, a dermatologist who plans to use the Half Moon as a platform to give history lessons on Dutch contributions. <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> himself was born in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> but was working for the <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> at the time he found the river that bears his name. There's a `` historical blind spot'' that keeps historians from considering Dutch contributions to the New World, <PERSON> Hendricks </PERSON> said. That's partly because the English ousted the Dutch from their early stronghold in the New World in the 1600s, he said. The Dutch first settled the area between English colonies in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, the nation's oldest incorporated city, he said. The ship will spend the summer touring the states once called the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> _ <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. At the christening, <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> Consul General <PERSON> Adrien </PERSON> <PERSON> Tieleman </PERSON> said the Dutch have always been proud of their `` small contribution to the mightiest, most free and prosperous nation in the world.'' The Half Moon replica cost about $ 1 million, raised mostly through donations, and took a year to build. The builders are applying finishing touches and the ship's maiden voyage is scheduled for July 5. About 25 people worked to build the square-rigged ship, which will be outfitted with replicas of 17th century cannons, said shipwright <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mayville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> Sailmaker <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bierig </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, hand-sewed the ship's nine sails. About 600 man-hours went into the sails, made of synthetics treated to look like canvas sails of the 1600s, he said. Because ships four centuries ago were built for cargo, the squat Half Moon wo n't win any races, <PERSON> Bierig </PERSON> said. `` It will be on the slow side,'' he said. `` Sailors were cheap and in those days there was no reason you needed speed.''
</TEXT>
