<FIRST>u i AM-China-Propaganda Bjt   06-11 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Propaganda, Bjt,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Propaganda Campaign Gives Government Side of Events</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-China, Bjt ^By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist Chinese propaganda machine is working at a frenzied pace to portray the bloody military occupation of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> as a heroic operation against `` counter-revolutionaries.'' The saturation campaign serves to shield the government from blame for the June 4 massacre in which hundreds, perhaps thousands of people died when soldiers fired at unarmed citizens supporting a movement for a freer society. Word of the assault on the pro-democracy movement quickly spread to several large <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> cities, where huge crowds took to the streets to demand the fall of conservative leaders who ordered the military attack. But hardliners such as senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> and Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> have kept their grip on power, supporting their position with the propaganda barrage. The main vehicle for the campaign has been nationwide television. After a few days of virtual silence on the attack, television began showing grainy black-and-white tapes of angry crowds attacking soldiers and torching military vehicles. Color videotapes of similar scenes soon appeared, often shown dozens of times over several days. Soldiers indiscriminately firing at crowds or crushing people with armored vehicles were not shown. Neither were scenes of hospitals filled with the dead and the injured from the withering attack on <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square. The videotapes often did not have sound, perhaps so the audience could not hear the gunfire or the angry chants of `` fascists'' directed at the soldiers. The official theme of soldiers as victims soon was expanded, with television showing injured troops lying in hospital beds. In one particularly gruesome scene, an evening newscast showed the charred bodies of three soldiers burned to death, including one who was disemboweled. The campaign also stresses the theme of soldiers as friends. Under guard of rifle-toting soldiers, propaganda trucks with signs reading `` the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> loves the people'' rolled down <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s main streets with loudspeakers blaring Scenes of soldiers and citizens helping one another have dominated television, which in recent days have devoted several hours of special newscasts daily to present the government line. On Saturday, television showed a peasant bringing three huge pigs to applauding soldiers. The next day's evening newscast showed troops at an elementary school playing with children and helping them clean their classrooms. The newest phase of the propaganda onslaught has shown dozens of `` scoundrels'' and `` counterrevolutionaries'' under arrest on charges of participating in the demonstrations. Television has shown them questioned at gunpoint and signing confessions. Chinese media also has attacked the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government-funded <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, which has provided millions of Chinese with an independent account of the weekend bloodbath. In another attempt to quell non-official accounts, television Saturday urged viewers to turn in a `` rumor-monger'' who was shown giving a bloody account of the attack. On Sunday, the evening news reported his capture and the man was shown expressing remorse to security officials. Television interviews with citizens applauding the military action increased during the weekend. `` It gave use great satisfaction to see the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> go into the city and put down the turmoil,'' said one man. Several people who were interviewed said they were shocked by the attacks on soldiers seen on television. `` I was greatly pained to see <ORGANIZATION> PLA </ORGANIZATION> soldiers burned to death and beaten to death,'' primary school teacher <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Qing </PERSON> told a television reporter. Many Chinese are skeptical of the state-controlled media so it is impossible to know how many people find the propaganda campaign convincing. `` Not a single person will believe it,'' said one <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> student who claimed he saw more than 10 people shot in <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> by soldiers early June 4. But some Chinese who did not see the weekend events themselves could find the relentless television accounts persuasive. `` In <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, people know what happened. But those on the outside do not,'' said another <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> student. `` Most Chinese are peasants. They believe what the government says.''
</TEXT>
