<FIRST>r a AM-HandcuffCaper     06-11 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Handcuff Caper,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspects Find Way to Shatter Shackles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inmates being driven from one jail to another smilingly showed the officer guarding them their new discovery: that their seat belts made handy tools for breaking handcuffs. The sheriff's office and <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> did n't smile, though, and are warning officers nationwide of the technique. `` There is danger to every law enforcement officer in the country,'' said <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. Ten prisoners learned the seat belt trick while being taken from the downtown jail to the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Pike </PERSON> jail, and before the ride was over all were free, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said Saturday. `` When the deputy opened the back of the van, all 10 guys were smiling and said ` See what we did,''' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said, adding that each prisoner held up his arms to show broken handcuffs. The cuffs that go around each wrist are connected by a chain, attached to each cuff by a swivel that moves freely to ensure that the chain does n't twist. Seat belt clips have one or two holes or slots, that lock them into place with the buckle. The prisoners learned that jamming the swivel link through a hole on the clip stops the swivel from turning freely. `` A quick twist of the wrist, and the chain shears off at the cuff,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. The prank led <LOCATION> Franklin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> authorities to issue emergency bulletins to law enforcement agencies across the state Friday. Similar warnings also would be given nationwide, the sheriff said, and an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said an advisory would be placed in the agency's Law Enforcement Bulletin. `` Although only 10 people know the technique, I guarantee that the entire jail population, all 690 of them, will know how to do it before the day is up,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` The only people who wo n't know about it is law enforcement officers.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> ordered seat belts removed from jail vans. He also ordered that prisoners in police cars be cuffed with their hands behind their backs and that the seat belts be locked firmly across them. Handcuff manufacturers were contacted Friday and are studying ways of redesigning the handcuffs, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. The 10 inmates who revealed their discovery may regret the caper. The sheriff was not amused. `` Charge them with destruction of county property,'' he told deputies. `` We'll see how funny they think that is.''
