<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the East German government says President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal for a reduction in conventional arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is a welcome step that is in tune with <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact desires for speedy negotiations, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> also quoted <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON> in its Sunday edition as confirming that East German border guards have been ordered not to use deadly force to stop civilians who attempt to flee into <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> unless the soldiers are threatened themselves. In a two-hour interview conducted last Wednesday in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted the influential <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> leader as saying the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal for <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> nations to cut conventional arms is `` close to our striving for radical conventional disarmament.'' Questioned on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s call to `` lock in'' reductions in tanks, artillery, armed personnel carriers and other non-nuclear forces in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> during a 23-nation negotiation on Conventional Forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the paper quoted <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON> as replying: `` We are interested in having those proposals included in the negotiations, so that we can identify where the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Treaty states concur -LRB- with <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and those areas where more intensive negotiations are needed.'' As to nuclear arms, he said, `` We are in favor of the step-by-step elimination of tactical nuclear weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Of course we know that this ca n't be done in one stroke.'' He raised the possibility that each side might decide to `` keep, say, 10'' weapons. `` One has to enter negotiations and see what progress can be achieved,'' said <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON>, who is head of state and general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` Sometimes surprises even occur.'' He rejected <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s call for the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall to be torn down, but said his government wants `` to humanize the border regime'' as part of generally improving relations with <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON> said East German border guards are authorized to shoot people trying to flee the country only if the guards are in physical danger or if a soldier or other uniformed person is trying to desert. He did not say when the restrictions took effect, but Western officials have said the policy apparently was adopted as a goodwill gesture prior to <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in 1987. Although 190 people have died trying to flee <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> since the wall was built in 1961, there has been only one confirmed case since the 1987 <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON> visit to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>.
