<HEAD>Two Chinese Diplomats Defect at San Francisco Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `In Washington...', to UPDATE with no-comment
from State Department.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of protesters and even some police officers wept as two Chinese diplomats made a surprise and emotional public appeal for political asylum, and rally organizers Sunday predicted more defections. `` Many of my friends have lost their lives and we wanted to do something to show we support what they stood for,'' said one of the diplomats during a rally Saturday night against <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s repression of the pro-democracy movement. `` Compared to them, I am not brave at all,'' added the man, who was not immediately identified. `` They are brave for standing up for democracy in the face of death or imprisonment.'' The two men, identified as a vice consul for cultural affairs and an overseas affairs officer, told the crowd of 5,000 they decided to defect after <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> leaders launched a propaganda campaign claiming no citizens died in the clash. Chinese troops opened fire on tens of thousands of students and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> residents June 4 to put an end to the seven-week pro-democracy movement and the sit-in at the city's <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence estimates put the number of people slain in the hundreds and possibly the thousands. `` We are supposed to tell you that no one was injured or killed. Why? Because we are diplomats. But we wo n't fake it here. Before we are diplomats, we are Chinese and we are human beings,'' one of the men told the crowd. `` We are public servants, we are not slaves,'' he added. The whereabouts of the diplomats Sunday were not immediately known. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> would not release their names but confirmed the two requested political asylum. A bureau spokeswoman Sunday said only that their case would be handled by the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. A staffer in the office of <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ilchert </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> regional director, said Sunday morning the two had not filed an asylum request. He would not give his name. To obtain political asylum, an applicant must show a well-founded fear of persecution in their homeland. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Daria </PERSON> <PERSON> Novak </PERSON> said the department had no immediate comment on the situation. Telephone calls to the Chinese consulate went unanswered. Organizers at the rally and candlelight memorial said at first they refused to allow the consulate officials to address the crowd outside City Hall. Even later, when event organizers were convinced of their sincerity, three people were posted alongside the diplomats on stage to yank them off in case of trouble. `` We did n't know if they'd start a riot or what, and it was a complete surprise for everyone when they said what they did,'' said <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Wou </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION>, one of the sponsors of the rally. `` But then we were ecstatic and everybody was hugging them and crying and saying that they were true Chinese and very, very brave,'' <PERSON> Wou </PERSON> said. He said he saw several police officers weeping after the announcement. Wou and other rally organizers predicted there would be other defections from Chinese consulates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We are encouraging this sort of thing to happen and expect more people to come out of these consulates to freedom,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Lu </PERSON>, general coordinator of San Francisco-based Support Democracy in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. However, <PERSON> Wou </PERSON> said he expects most Chinese students eventually to return home to support the pro-democracy cause. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Man-kar </PERSON>, an editor at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, on Sunday identified the two from their business cards as <PERSON> Zhou </PERSON> <PERSON> Li-ming </PERSON>, 26, vice consul for cultural affairs, and <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Li-man </PERSON>, 25, acting consul for overseas affairs. He said both had been in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for 2 -LCB- years and were unmarried. He estimated that the total number of Chinese staff members and dependents at the consulate was 300 to 400. <PERSON> Wou </PERSON> said the diplomats told him they had walked to the rally after finishing dinner at the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consulate </ORGANIZATION>, about a half-mile away. On the way, they stopped at a public telephone and called the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, which escorted them to an undisclosed location from the rally. The defections were announced in Chinese and English at the protest, where a largely Asian crowd denounced the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> government. Many wore black arm bands and carried banners reading `` Their blood, Our tears.''
