<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> detonated its fourth underground nuclear bomb this year in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> government scientists said Sunday. The explosion of about 70 kilotons occurred Saturday at Fangatau atoll in <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Polynesia </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Warwick </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. It brings to 107 the number of underground tests <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> has conducted since it began nuclear tests in the region in 1975, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. This year the French exploded an 11-kiloton bomb on May 11, a two-kiloton bomb on May 20 and one of 20 kilotons on June 4. One kiloton is equivalent to blasting 1,000 tons of TNT. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> and other South Pacific nations question the safety of the tests and argue they escalate the arms race. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> refuses to confirm reports of nuclear testing.
