<FIRST>r a AM-MosaicsTrial     06-11 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosaics Trial,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mosaics Verdict Rests on Two Legal Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In an odd way, <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> art dealer <PERSON> Peg </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> feels honored. `` Very few people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have had the privilege of being sued not only by a country, but by a religion,'' <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said following the conclusion of a six-day civil trial in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last week. The Republic of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Autocephalous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> are demanding the return of four sixth-century Christian mosaics. Taken from a church in northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> in 1979, the works were purchased by <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> last summer. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> says she fell in love with the rare Byzantine pieces and purchased them for $ 1.1 million only after her investigation turned up no evidence they had been reported stolen. She later offered them for sale for $ 20 million, but they are off the market pending the outcome of the lawsuit. Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Noland </PERSON>'s decision, which is not expected until August at the earliest, could rest on two legal questions: _ Did <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> act recklessly and hastily when she purchased the mosaics during a four-day visit to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> in July _ Did <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> diligently seek the return of the mosaics and try to notify the international art community after it learned the works were stolen in 1979 At stake are not only the `` spiritual treasures'' of one of the earliest Christian religions, but also the status of antiquities in <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> museums and around the world, analysts say. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>'s actions were criticized in testimony from three witnesses: a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law professor and curators at the J. Paul Getty Museum in <LOCATION> Malibu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> Art Gallery in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, Md. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Vikan </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> gallery said the objects, circumstances and people involved in <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>'s purchase should have warned her away. Among those who brought <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> into the deal were an <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> art dealer who has used three names and a Dutchman who has been convicted of art forgery in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, court records show. The Dutchman, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Rijn </PERSON>, is well-known as a `` shady dealer'' who markets stolen art, <PERSON> Vikan </PERSON> testified. But <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> testified she liked <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Rijn </PERSON> and he seemed to have universal respect in <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>. `` There was n't anyplace that we went that somebody did n't come out of a shop and say, ` Hi, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>,''' she said. `` We were always bumping into people he would chat with and introduce me to.'' The roughly 2-foot-square mosaics _ which depict the heads of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> as a boy, the apostles <PERSON> James </PERSON> and <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> and an archangel _ were taken from a war-torn area of northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> under control of a breakaway Turkish state recognized only by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vikan </PERSON> testified he would have walked away from the purchase. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> art dealer <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmerich </PERSON>, a former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said he might have gone ahead. `` When confronted by a really major work of art, and it's perfectly clear the piece is authentic and of unequaled quality, I might well have proceeded the same way My God, yes,'' <PERSON> Emmerich </PERSON> testified on <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>'s behalf. <PERSON> Emmerich </PERSON> also testified he felt <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> had left `` no stone unturned'' in her investigation. `` I think her inquiry met the best professional standards,'' <PERSON> Emmerich </PERSON> said. `` I could n't have expected more.'' <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> seemed incredulous at the suggestion she would sacrifice her business and the livelihood of her partner, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldman </PERSON>, by purchasing stolen artwork. `` Who in their right mind can imagine that we would borrow one million dollars to buy stolen property?'' she said. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>'s attorneys tried to prove <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> gave up claim to the mosaics when Greek Cypriots fled the village of <LOCATION> Lythrankomi </LOCATION> in 1976, leaving the church and its mosaics unattended. Turkish forces had taken control of the area, stifling the rights of <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> citizens, Greek Cypriots testified. `` Did, in fact, southern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> have a right to lay claim to something in northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>?'' <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> asked. Six Greek Cypriot officials testified how they tried to recover the mosaics against political and bureaucratic roadblocks erected by the division of their country. They said they notified museums and agencies of the theft, issued press releases and sent representatives to speak about stolen Cypriot antiquities at international art conferences. However, none of them could say they had notified <ORGANIZATION> Interpol </ORGANIZATION>, an international police agency, or tried to pursue <PERSON> Aydin </PERSON> <PERSON> Dikmen </PERSON>, the Turk who sold the mosaics to <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> and who had been publicly linked to the mosaics in 1982.
