<HEAD>Agreement Seems Near on Early Exit for Alfonsin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> will assume power several months ahead of schedule in an agreement being worked out with <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s lame-duck leader, <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, officials said Sunday. The arrangement would allow <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> to begin tackling the nation's crippling economic problems sometime this summer, rather than wait until December, when he is scheduled to take over from President <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> `` I have no doubt he does n't want to stay until Dec. 10,'' <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Casella </PERSON>, an official of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said of <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. `` There will be an accord shortly.'' <PERSON> Casella </PERSON> was the governing party candidate for vice president in the May 14 elections, which were won by <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Under the constitution, <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> is scheduled to take office on Dec. 10. But with the economy in chaos and food riots in early June that left 14 dead, many people have called on <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> to step aside sooner. Although no date was set in weekend talks between the two main parties, <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> might hand over power in the first half of August, said <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> senate </ORGANIZATION> president and a key adviser to his older brother. President-elect <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> has said he wo n't push <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> to step down early. But last week, after he appointed a Cabinet and fleshed out an economic plan, the <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> said he was prepared to take power any time. Shortly after the <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> election landslide, <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> offered to step down early, but he could not agree with <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> on terms. The main differences were over economic policies and how <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> could leave office without resigning. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> also insisted that <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> congressmen who won election with him take office when he does and that the trials of military officers charged with human rights abuse during the 1976-83 dictatorship be resolved by <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. The military `` situation stems from the current government and I consider it convenient that the answer and the solution be granted by this government,'' <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> said. In an apparent solution worked out over the weekend, the <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> would meet early to confirm <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s victory and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would modify the law that sets the transition day. That would allow <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> to step down without resigning. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> congressmen would agree to support whatever legislation <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> deemed necessary to stabilize the economy, which has soared out of control under <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. Hyperinflation, economic recession and high unemployment caused food riots in which Argentines looted supermarkets and grocery stores. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> declared a nationwide state of siege. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> has tried to cut the budget deficit _ a main cause of inflation _ by cutting government spending and raising tariffs for public services. The measures, coupled with inflation expected to reach 70 percent this month, have torn into pocketbooks and prompted cries for <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> to leave office early. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> has said the higher rates are `` anti-popular.'' Measures reportedly being developed by the economy minister-designate, <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Roig </PERSON>, include an across-the-board wage raise, easy access to <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> credit, and a new currency to replace the austral. It was unclear how the military issue, which has brought on three insurrections against <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, would be resolved. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> took office in December 1983 for a six-year term after elections that ended rule by military dictators since 1976. He was barred by the consitution from seeking re-election.
