<HEAD>Two Million Flock to Khomeini Memorial Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Iranians died and thousands fainted as huge crowds flocked to the grave of <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> on Sunday for a memorial service marking a week since his death. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s most powerful leaders were among the more than 1 million mourners at <LOCATION> Beheshte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zahra </LOCATION> cemetery, 10 miles south of <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, according to Iranian press reports monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>. `` Soon this site will become a shrine to attract the Moslems of the world,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, who broke into tears during his speech. `` This is a center which radiates heavenly light.'' In Islam, the seventh and 40th days after death are considered a time for special mourning rites. Free food and drink was distributed around the grave. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s state-run television showed mourners beating their heads and chests with clenched fists in the Shiite Moslem expression of grief and chanting `` <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, why did you leave us?'' But the atmosphere appeared calmer than during Tuesday's burial, which was delayed for six hours after some in the hysterical crowd of 2 million tore pieces from <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s white shroud and sent the body falling to the ground. The 86-year-old patriarch died June 3 after suffering a heart attack. There were eight deaths and 11,000 injuries in subsequent three days of mourning. On Sunday, one man died of a heart attack and another died after falling from a cargo container used for television cameras, according to press reports. The official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the mourners were so densely packed during the afternoon ceremony that on average one person fainted every second in temperatures around 96. The sick were passed overhand to one of 23 mobile medical units stationed around the site and more than 1,000 doctors and medical workers were on duty, the news agency reported. More serious injuries were rushed to nearby hospitals in one of 250 ambulances. The television, also monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, showed a shrine built from four metal cargo containers to stop crowds from carrying off the dirt. The containers were covered in green, a holy color for Islam, and were topped with a golden dome and a black flag. The television showed weeping mourners gripping a metal grille built around the structure, trying to touch and kiss the shrine, which they consider sacred. Those unable to reach it threw clothes and other articles to the guards standing on top the containers. The guards touched them to the shrine and threw them back. `` It would take a stone heart to stay composed at such a time,'' <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> said in his speech. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s 43-year-old son, <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON>, was reported too overcome to speak. A crop-dusting plane sprayed rosewater on the mourners, and helicopters circled overhead, showering the crowds with flowers. The agency said crowds began collecting at the grave site on Saturday night and swelled to almost 2 miles wide. There were unprecedented traffic jams on the expressway leading to the cemetery. In a related development, Iranian opposition leaders said exiled Iranians living in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> have flocked to rebel training camps, reopened after the death of <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, a guerrilla spokesman said Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, the armed wing of the Baghdad-based <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION>, received many new supporters in the past week and sent them to camps on the Iraq-Iran border, according to spokesman <PERSON> Farid </PERSON> <PERSON> Suliamani </PERSON>. The camps were closed after the Aug. 20 U.N.-mediated cease-fire in the eight-year Iran-Iraq war then reopened in a show of strength following <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s death, according to diplomatic sources. They said, however, there was no indication the rebels would attack <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in violation of the cease-fire. The rebels fought alongside <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the gulf war.
