<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Sees Bright Future For Hungary ... Unless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With accelerating economic reform and political liberalization, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> could emerge as a `` Western country'' within the next decade, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> said Sunday. At the same time, Ambassador <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> cautioned that under certain conditions the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> might again use military force to reassert its control in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> or elsewhere in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` I think the <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> <PERSON> Doctrine </PERSON> is not dead, that there are circumstances under which the Soviets would intervene,'' he said. `` <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s a little less of a concern to them, I would say, than the militarily more important countries of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, but I would not rule out the possibility of their intervening again.'' Under the <ORGANIZATION> Brezhnev </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doctrine </ORGANIZATION>, named for late Soviet President <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> reserved the right to intervene _ as it did in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> in 1956 and in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> in 1968 _ to preserve communist regimes in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, interviewed on the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> program `` This Week With <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinkley </PERSON>,'' was asked about the longer-term prospects for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, which recently began taking down its `` Iron Curtain'' barbed wire and fortifications along its border with <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. The envoy said the outlook depends partly on what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other Western nations do. `` If we come into these countries with our political parties, our trade unions, with our ideas, our values and our institutions, our churches, our universities, our foundations, I think there's a real chance that what you will see 10 years from today in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> is a Western country,'' <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> said. Also interviewed on the program was <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, where candidates backed by the Solidarity movement won a resounding victory in parliamentary elections last week. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> was asked whether Solidarity would now be a permanent political force in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, or could be suppressed again in a way comparable to the martial law crackdown in 1981. `` I think it's back to stay,'' he replied. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> added: `` I think that Solidarity has proved through its nonviolence, its responsible attitude and its willingness to share power in the country that it is a partner that the government can look forward to working with. `` In fact, the situation now is that the government in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, the communist government, can not pass any legislation without the agreement of Solidarity,'' the ambassador said.
