<HEAD>Dukakis Walks Tightrope in Signing Chelsea School Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An unprecedented experiment in public education is about to begin with Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> expected to sign a bill Monday that will let <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> take over the troubled school system in the city of <LOCATION> Chelsea </LOCATION>. The plan, approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> after months of sometimes bitter discussion, will link a public school system with one of the highest dropout rates in the state _ 17 percent _ to a world-class university with all its financial and educational resources. <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> will get the prestige of conducting an educational experiment never before tried in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, one that will be watched closely and possibly duplicated by universities around the country. `` One of the things I think we'd like to encourage in this state is innovation and experimentation,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` And there's no question this is innovative and experimental.'' `` We have a bill which I think has real promise for the future of the schoolchildren in <LOCATION> Chelsea </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` It's an experiment, and like most experiments, it is one that has to be tried before we know whether it will succeed.'' Under the plan, <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> will run the 3,600-student system for 10 years and pump in money from private donors and foundations for a variety of new programs, including early childhood education, counseling and nutritional services. <PERSON> Chelsea </PERSON> schools have been woefully underfunded, according to officials in the largely Hispanic, working-class city of 25,000 outside <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Chelsea </PERSON> has seen its tax base shrink and faces cuts of about $ 2.8 million in next year's school budget because of a state budget crunch. <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION>'s refusal to agree to any language guaranteeing open meetings while orally promising to abide by state open-meeting laws had held up the bill and had put <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in a difficult position once the measure reached his desk. Local teachers unions and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, which endorsed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in his bid for president last year, had complained that the pact would allow <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> to make decisions behind closed doors. But a veto would have set up <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for an embarrassment, since the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> had passed the bill with enough votes to override. On Friday, however, the governor said he would sign the bill _ and also direct the <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> to set up a monitoring panel to make sure BU abides by the open-meeting and public-records laws. That move seemed to satisfy several factions that were practically at one another's throats days earlier. <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> administrators were delighted with the announcement, saying it allowed them to begin raising the roughly $ 30 million they hope to spend over the next decade. Hispanics opposed the agreement, saying university officials have ignored requests for more information about bilingual programs. <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Silber </PERSON> said he would heed concerns raised. `` We are not going to privatize the schools,'' <PERSON> Silber </PERSON> said. `` We are going to manage the public schools and they are going to remain public.'' For higher education there could be a long-term benefit if the BU experiment succeeds. `` Universities are looking at themselves and saying, ` What is our role in terms of the reform movement in education?''' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Greer </PERSON>, dean of the <ORGANIZATION> BU </ORGANIZATION> education school. `` One thing universities have said is say how bad the entering freshmen are.''
