<HEAD>New Orleans Board to Vote on Year-Round School Experiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Summer may be over almost before it's begun for students at two elementary schools where officials are planning to try the Three Rs year-round. The <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> meets Monday to make its final decison, after giving tentative approval in February to add 40 days to the school year at the two city schools. For pupils at <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Moton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lockett </PERSON> elementary schools who volunteer to take part, it would mean returning to school July 10 instead of Sept. 5 like the rest of the city's students The schools have a combined enrollment of 1,400. Its estimated cost would be $ 703,000 and some supporters fear board members might balk at the expense of the plan when they meet on Monday. `` We really have to try a model to work out the kinks,'' board member <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON> said Sunday. He said he expects a unanimous vote, even though some board members may have reservations about parts of the plan. `` It's expensive but it's worth spending the money to try it out.'' Plans call for the money to come from the federal government's Chapter I supplemental program for disadvantaged students _ about three-quarters of the students at each school are from low-income families, <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON> said But federal rather than local tax dollars wo n't mean the program will be judged any less strictly, he said. `` It has to prove that it's cost-effective and can improve test scores and deportment in the schools,'' said <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON>. `` We will see after the first year how well this program is judged.'' He said the program is planned for both <PERSON> Moton </PERSON>, which had 798 students last year, and <PERSON> Lockett </PERSON>, which had 710, because they serve students from the same general area _ an area which includes two housing projects. `` Sometimes the kids move around. We do n't want a situation where they move from one school to another and lose the services,'' he said. <PERSON> Nelka </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> is one parent who will be disappointed if the year-round plan is postponed. `` Year-round school is a plus,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who was at <LOCATION> Moton </LOCATION> on Thursday to pick up report cards for her five children, all of whom made the honor roll and earned perfect attendance certificates. `` A longer school year would give the children something better to do than playing in the street, especially in that dirty water after it rains,'' she said. Like other <PERSON> Moton </PERSON> parents, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said the year-round program will give the children an alternative to the drugs and violence prevalent in the nearby Desire housing project area. `` I'd rather see them here safe than exposed to drugs in the streets,'' said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>, whose three children attend <PERSON> Moton </PERSON>. `` Three months without nothing to do is too much time wasted.'' While most American children spend 180 days in the classroom, school terms in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> last 240 days. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> experiment would be for a 220-day term. Two American high schools offer an extended year. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> has year-round schools, <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON> said, but that program was started because there were too few school buildings rather than as an attempt to boost learning. <PERSON> Moton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lockett </PERSON> teachers were given the option of transferring to other schools, and student participation is voluntary. <PERSON> Lockett </PERSON> <PERSON> Principal </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said all but two of his teachers signed up for the year-round program. `` The 