in the war and also halted operations inside <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> following the truce. But rebel leaders put their forces _ estimated at 20,000 _ on alert after <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> underwent surgery May 23 to stop intestinal bleeding. After the patriarch's death, opposition leader <PERSON> Massoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajavi </PERSON> called on Iranians to prepare to welcome the rebels and help them when they move into <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> `` at the appropriate moment.'' Rebel camps were reopened in a show of force, diplomats said. The diplomatic sources spoke on the condition they not be identified. But there has been no indication that the rebels are planning military action. Military analysts do not believe the rebels are strong enough to topple the Iranian government alone unless a power struggle develops. And despite earlier indications of factional fighting, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s new leader, President <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> seems to be consolidating his position, sources said. In addition, any military move would need approval from the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> government. It is thought unlikely that <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> would permit any action that might jeopardize the temporary truce with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> or impede progress in deadlocked peace talks. One diplomat said although it was unlikely the rebels would move across the border while the cease-fire holds they might take advantage of any serious truce violation to attack Iranian positions or set up rebel bases inside <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> officials said the group's military strength has increased steadily since the cease-fire and that months of intensive training in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have made it `` a far more effective military force than before.'' The rebels were allied with <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> in the struggle to topple the late <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSO