<FIRST>u a AM-Iowa-Gunpowder     06-11 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iowa-Gunpowder,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Changes Gunpowder Storage Practices After Iowa Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is changing the way it stores gunpowder for 16-inch guns on its Iowa-class battleships, despite indications that powder was not at fault in the fatal blast on the battleship <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. When the battleship <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> heads for maintenance and repairs this summer, its powder charges _ 110-pound bags _ will not be stored aboard uncooled, unventilated barges as the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s were, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials told The Virginian-Pilot and The Ledger-Star of <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>. When the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> went in for similar overhaul during the summer of 1988, its powder was stored aboard uncooled barges at the Yorktown Naval Weapons Station on the <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> during the hottest part of the summer. In April, 47 sailors aboard the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> were killed when powder exploded in the No. 2 gun turret during open seas gunnery practice. Before the explosion, the No. 1 turret had a misfire when the five bags of powder used to propel the gun's projectile would n't ignite. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials have said they do not believe the storage of the powder was to blame and are investigating the possibility of sabotage. Nevertheless, the charges aboard the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> have been removed and replaced with powder that was stored in temperature-controlled underground bunkers. Smokeless powder is less stable and less effective `` if it is stored in damp atmosphere or subjected to high temperatures. A combination of the two is particularly bad,'' according to <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manual </ORGANIZATION> OP5, the service's guide to munition storage. The manual says the powder charges decompose faster at temperatures above 70 degrees Fahrenheit, `` becoming relatively high at 100 degrees Fahrenheit and dangerously accelerated at temperatures above 110 degrees Fahrenheit.'' An internal <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> report estimates the temperature inside the aluminum-sided barges used for storage was 25 degrees higher than the outside air temperature. Using that estimate, the newspaper calculated from <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> readings for the area that the temperature inside the barges could have exceeded 110 degrees on 66 days at the time the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s powder was in storage. The newspaper, quoting internal memos from the station's safety officer to his superiors, said the station's command was urged to remove the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s powder charges from the barges anchored at piers on the river bank. `` Permitting these charges to be stored in the barge for this period of time indicates the lack of importance that is placed on compliance with the safety requirements'' set forth in the manual on munition storage, a September 1988 memo said. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, administrative officer at the <LOCATION> Yorktown </LOCATION> station, said the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s powder would not be stored at the station, the largest of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s six weapon stations. `` If it was for a short period, it would be something different. We'll move it inland, and then bring it back when it's needed,'' he said. <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said additional magazines are being built at the weapons station to accommodate more munitions. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Yorktown </PERSON> is the only one of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s munitions stations that uses barges for temporary powder storage. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is continuing its investigation into the explosion, and has regularly declined to comment on its findings until the investigation is complete. Preliminary tests by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> powder have not shown any indications of instability, according to the Pentagon.
</TEXT>
