<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hungarian television on Sunday showed brief film footage of the trial of Premier <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON>, a leader of the 1956 anti-Soviet revolt who was executed in 1958. <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> and the bodies of several of his close associates were buried in unmarked graves, but the remains are to be reburied during a ceremony Friday. Reformers, including <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members, have claimed <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> and the others were convicted at an unconstitutional `` show trial'' and said they should be `` rehabilitated.'' The film clip showed <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> and some of his supporters being led into a courtroom where they were charged with crimes against the state. It was shown during a half-hour news program on the 1956 revolt when <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON>'s government sought to organize multiparty free elections and sever <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s ties with the Soviet-led <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact alliance. Soviet tanks crushed the revolt and <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> and hundreds of other government and political leaders were arrested. The bodies of <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> and a few associates were dumped in a grave in a cemetery in suburban Budpest. During Friday's ceremony, which will be televised, the remains will be buried again in the same cemetery. Re-evaluation of the revolt began after hard-line <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>, who succeeded <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON>, was ousted in May 1988 under strong criticism from reformers. In a statement last week the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership called <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> a `` significant'' figure in post-World War II <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Leading Communist reformer <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON>, in an intervie