<HEAD>Methanol Fire To Be Allowed to Burn Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLAQUEMINE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 2.5 million-gallon tank of methanol set afire by lightning continued to burn Sunday as officials allowed it to burn itself out. `` According to what they say, it should be burned out before daylight,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Iberville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION>'s Deputy <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hebert </PERSON>. `` The tank is folding in as the fire burns itself down,'' <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Lansford </PERSON>, manager at the six-month-old <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plant where the tank was located, said late Saturday. He said there was little danger the fire would spread to nearby tanks. Just to be sure, state police said, firefighters sprayed water on the burning tank and another tank of methanol, or methyl alcohol, about 400 feet away to keep them as cool as possible. Damage appeared to be confined to the tank and no injuries were reported. The plant turns natural gas into methanol, a high-quality fuel used for, among other things, drag racers. The fire was reported Saturday afternoon.
