</PERSON>. <PERSON> Mallick </PERSON> had been accused of providing <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> with a phony job and improper gifts. As negotiations continued, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> turned down offers that would have included continuing the censure over the sale of his book, `` Reflections of a Public Man,'' and the stipulation that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> step down within 24 hours. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> reportedly said there would be no `` quid pro quo'' agreement for his resignation in exchange for exoneration on charges. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s representatives met with the committee's outside counsel, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said he had votes of all six Republicans and at least one Democrat, Rep. <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON>, D-Mass., to continue the investigation into other allegations against <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> for several months When those talks failed, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., then the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority leader and now the Speaker, was called in as a mediator The relationship between <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> had deteriorated to the point that neither man trusted the other, the newspaper reported. Then the ethics committee convened, with some Republicans reportedly angered by the negotiations. But three hours later, the group had heard nothing from <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. `` If he wanted to make an offer, we were sitting there,'' said Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Indiana </LOCATION>, who added that he was opposed to any deals. To <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s closest allies, the former speaker was the victim of a `` setup.'' But <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATIO