<HEAD>Fiftieth Anniversary Celebrated Of King's Visit To Roosevelt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HYDE PARK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Friends of former President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> celebrated Sunday the 50th anniversary of King <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> VI </PERSON>'s visit to <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Park </PERSON>, believed to have strengthened U.S.-Anglo relations on the eve of World War II About 250 people turned out at the <ORGANIZATION> Franklin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> on the grounds of the <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION> home, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, library director. <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s King <PERSON> George </PERSON> and <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> visited <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>'s home June 11, 1939, during a tour of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Sunday's celebration began the same way the king and queen's visit did, with morning prayers at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> British Amabassador <PERSON> Antony </PERSON> <PERSON> Acland </PERSON> read an Episcopalian lesson similar to the service attended by the <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelts </ORGANIZATION> and the king and queen in 1939. <PERSON> Acland </PERSON> opened a special exhibit at the FDR Library that includes the king's notes on conversations he had with <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> about how the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> might help <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> against <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Acland </PERSON> also read a message from Queen <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> reminiscing about her 1939 visit. <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> invited the king and queen as part of his strateg