<HEAD>Jackson, Dukakis March Together Against Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> marched together in an anti-drug parade and rally that drew thousands of people Sunday. The two former Democratic presidential candidates exchanged only a few civilities before <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> addressed the rally in City Hall Plaza, urging residents to drive drug-pushing `` terrorists'' out of their neighborhoods. `` We do n't need no police to drive drug pushers out. We must drive them out,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told several thousand people who attended the rally, dubbed <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drugs </ORGANIZATION> or BAD. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was criticized last week for accepting a $ 15,000 fee for the appearance. He said he did not request the money, which came from business sponsors of the anti-drug effort and was offered to him by city officials. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said the money would go to his political organization, the <ORGANIZATION> Rainbow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, rather than into his own pocket. `` <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> gets $ 25,000 for his own personal aggrandizement,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, referring to speeches given by the former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> staffer. `` It's perfectly reasonable -LRB- to accept the $ 15,000 fee -RRB- and it's a proper thing to do. It came from people who can afford it.'' Before the rally, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> briefly marched together in a parade through the city. The meeting was one of the first since between <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> since the governor's presidential bid fell short in November. Aides said they shook hands and said hello cordially but did not have time for any substantive discussions.
