<HEAD>Apple Commission Rejects Call for Labeling Alar-Treated Apples</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WENATCHEE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has rejected a call to put special labels on boxes of Alar-treated apples. Commissioners voted instead Friday to ask growers to approve an emergency assessment of 25 cents a box to pay for additional advertising to move the remaining 1988 crop. Some 12 million boxes of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> apples are in storage now, about 4.5 million more than last year. To sell that inventory before the 1989 crop arrives will require moving about 682,000 boxes of apples a week, executive director <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said. That compares to the past two summers' average of 425,000 boxes a week, he said. The emergency assessment must be ratified by growers, and then come back to the commission for final approval. It would be in effect only between July 1 and Aug. 30. The manufacturer of Alar, <ORGANIZATION> Uniroyal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, announced June 2 it was taking the substance off the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market immediately to help rebuild consumer confidence. Alar is the marketing name for daminozide, a growth regulator that enhances the appearance of apples and increases their shelf life. It was labeled a possible carcinogen by the private <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in a February report. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> subsequently announced it plans to ban Alar next year. The commission's advertising money is depleted now, but a proposed $ 2 million supplemental advertising program funded by the assessment would promote apples as a portable summer fruit, and try to lure customers with sweepstakes and cash prizes. The commission had sent a questionnaire to growers, asking, in part, whether `` All <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> apple cartons should be labeled ` Alar' or ` No Alar' for the remainder of the 1988 crop.'' In the results announced Friday, 689 growers said yes and 734 said no. Several commissioners said they thought segregating Alar-treated apples would be harmful to the industry. They also said it would be counterproductive to the commission's plan to erase the word `` Alar'' the public's mind. The Alar controversy already has cost <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> growers more than $ 77 million this year, and nationwide has cost growers more than $ 100 million, <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> has said.
