<HEAD>Chrysler Drops Interest-Free Financing For Many Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Analysts say a decision by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to drop 2-month-old interest-free financing on most models may be a sign the No. 3 automaker will adopt other incentive programs. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> on Friday altered the incentive package by offering cash rebates ranging from $ 500 to $ 2,000 and interest rates as low as 2.9 percent for the bulk of its car and truck line. The program runs indefinitely. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s move brings it closer to incentive programs at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jeannette </PERSON> <PERSON> Garretty </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> said the move could indicate other incentives are planned `` The issue that is facing all of the manufacturers right now is with sales not as high or not responding as quickly to the incentives that have been put out there, the question is what do they do,'' she said. `` Do they have to take them off for a little while in order to be able to trumpet a whole new this-is-it, end-of-the-year clearance? There are going to be all sorts of deals.'' Chrysler began offering interest-free financing on two-year loans for all of its cars and some of its light trucks on April 3. Effective Monday, the automaker said, no-interest, two-year loans would be available only on six cars and trucks. During April, about half of the loans written by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the automaker's financing arm, were zero percent, said spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Heath </PERSON>. Figures for May are not yet available, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales were down 2.9 percent and truck sales were up 5.5 percent in April compared with April 1988. Typically, less than 25 percent of the automobile buyers going through financing arms of the Big Three automakers choose two-year loans. <PERSON> Garretty </PERSON> speculated that most Chrysler buyers who chose two-year loans already were in the car market, and were ready with large down payments.
