<HEAD>Newspaper Industry Technology Exposition Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Printing presses, newsroom computers and other equipment filled two <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> convention centers at the opening of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> technology exposition. More than 300 exhibitors spread out over 320,000 square feet to show off the latest equipment for the big business of newspapering. `` I'm a little overwhelmed. There's a lot to see. It's very impressive,'' <PERSON> Alix </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> News </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said Saturday, the first day of the exhibition. As many as 15,000 people are expected to attend the five-day <ORGANIZATION> ANPA </ORGANIZATION> `` Protocols for Progress'' convention, said registration manager <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>. The formal conference gets under way Monday and concludes Wednesday. The meeting coincides with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> conference, also in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> Monday through Wednesday. Exhibitors showed how computers can be used to do everything from laying out newspaper pages to designing graphics. One company even offers a robot that changes printing plates on the press. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said some of the most interesting displays involve `` open architecture'' systems, computer systems that integrate equipment from different manufacturers. `` I think that's the future,'' he said.
