<HEAD>India Will Not Negotiate on U.S. Trade Act</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> will not negotiate with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over its citation for violating the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Omnibus Trade Act, under which <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> faces retaliatory tariffs for what <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> calls unfair trade laws, <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. The news agency on Saturday quoted unidentified government officials as saying that negotiations on trade could not be held under threat of retaliation. Last month, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> cited <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> under section 301 of the 1988 trade act for impeding direct foreign investment and closing the Indian insurance market to foreign companies. The law allows the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to impose tariffs of 100 percent on goods from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> if negotiations fail to remove the barriers within 18 months. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had suggested that negotiations to remove the barriers begin not later than June 16. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s largest trading partner and two-way trade between the nations was about $ 5.7 billion in 1988. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> held a trading surplus of about $ 700 million dollars.
