<HEAD>Head of Italy's Dominant Merchant Bank Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Italian magistrate has charged the head of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s dominant merchant bank, <ORGANIZATION> Mediobanca </ORGANIZATION>, with deceitful bookkeeping, newspapers reported Sunday. Milan Investigating Magistrate <PERSON> Gherardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Colombo </PERSON> charged <PERSON> Enrico </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuccia </PERSON> with registering the equivalent of $ 17 million under a false heading in <ORGANIZATION> Mediobanca </ORGANIZATION>'s balance sheets during the years 1976-1980. <PERSON> Cuccia </PERSON> and other bank officials have said they are innocent of the charges. Investigators did not reveal the alleged destination of the funds. Newspapers said investigators believed the money was likely paid under the table to accountants, construction workers or others performing services for the bank. Additionally, the newspapers reported, the money probably was used to give bank employees bonuses and to improve ailing balances of some of the bank's client companies. <PERSON> Cuccia </PERSON>, an 81-year-old financial wizard, has headed the bank, which is part state-owned and part private, since it was founded in 1946. He formally retired in 1982 but has stayed on as honorary president. Investigations into the alledged diversion of funds began about ten years ago and seemed to have reached a halt in 1984, when prosecutors recommended the case be dismissed. <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> magistrates instead continued examining the case and have issued a summons for the elderly banker and four other people who were top officials of the bank during the second half of the 1970s.
