<HEAD>Kemp Upset By Allegations That Millions Embezzled From HUD</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Kemp reported upset by allegations,
other details. A version moving on national wire under AM-Robin HUD.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of Housing and Urban Development <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> is `` very upset'' by allegations that millions of dollars were embezzled from the department by private escrow agents, including claims by a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> woman that she siphoned off $ 5.5 million to give to the poor, a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> official said Sunday. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> ordered <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Inspector General <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> to conduct an immediate investigation of alleged embezzlement in <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> field office and on Friday <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> placed four employees on leave without pay, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s general counsel-designee, said. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported the embezzlement losses could reach $ 10 million in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office, while <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said investigations also were under way in <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> offices in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> about million-dollar diversions. In <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reba </PERSON> <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovell </PERSON> has been indicted on charges she embezzled $ 2.5 million from the sale of 55 homes in the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> area. A two-year investigation in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office led to an inspector general's audit. <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON>, an escrow agent in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> whom federal investigators have dubbed `` <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> HUD </PERSON>,'' claimed that extraordinarily lax management allowed her to divert as much as $ 5.5 million during a four-year period to help feed, clothe and house the poor in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` I figured that as long as I was going to go to jail anyway, I would help a few people with the time I had left,'' the 46-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hills </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, resident told the Times. In a telephone interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday, <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> said that based upon what he has read in the newspapers, `` I'm outraged, and I know the secretary is extremely upset that acts like this could take place, although as noted all of them allegedly took place prior to him taking office.'' <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> would not comment directly on <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON>'s allegations. Attempts to contact <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> were not successful. <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> ordered a full investigation by the inspector general's office and an accounting firm `` to determine the extent of the problem, suggest remedies and construct a system which will make this kind of conduct infrequent if not impossible in the future.'' `` The fact that in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> a closing agent could allegedly embezzle $ 2 million and not be noticed, the fact that in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> a closing agent could allegedly give $ 5 million to the poor and not be noticed shows serious mangement deficiencies, and the secretary intends to see that that conduct does not recur,'' <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> said. The investigation is separate from a congressional inquiry into allegations that influence-peddling at <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> allowed more than a dozen former <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials to benefit from housing programs meant for the poor. As an escrow agent, <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> collected money from the sales of property that had been foreclosed by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The properties originally had been purchased with HUD-guaranteed loans. Agents such as <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> handle the closing on the foreclosures and turn over the sales proceeds to the government while keeping a small commission. But in 1985, she used some of the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> money to cover a $ 37,000 shortfall in her business, <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. When several months passed without an inquiry from <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, it became clear to her the department was so poorly run that it was unable to track the millions in dollars in payments due from escrow agents, she said. She took more money _ as much as $ 5.5 million, by her estimate _ before anyone noticed. Investigators believe she bought 20 homes and nearly 40 automobiles for the needy. She told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> in an interview published Sunday that some of the money may have become `` mingled'' into improvements on her home that included a swimming pool, a $ 2,500 wide-screen television and renovations to her basement. But she said she used her home as a homeless shelter and therefore she could justify the expenses. She said she now has transferred the home to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> in an attempt to offset her financial problems. Her scheme began to unravel last year, she said, when a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> official in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> field office, <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON>, detected the diversion. <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON> would not comment when contacted Sunday, but his attorney, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, was quoted by the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> as saying <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON>'s suspension was `` an outrage.'' `` Rothshcild is the person who came in and tried to do something about this,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON> is chief of the property disposition division of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> field office. <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> said <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON> was placed on leave without pay along with <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, who heads the office; <ORGANIZATION> Robert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>, director of housing management; and <PERSON> Charle </PERSON> <PERSON> Womble </PERSON>, a supervisory loan specialist. <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> faces questioning by a grand jury in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and says she is cooperating with investigators trying to track the diverted funds. She told the Times she was relieved her activities finally were out in the open. `` Christians are n't perfect,'' she was quoted as saying. `` They're just forgiven.''
