<HEAD>Memo Criticizes Bank's Auto Insurance Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> attorney warned in a confidential memo six months ago the bank could be subject to penalties as a result of some insurance charges imposed on thousands of auto loan customers in 1987 and 1988. Attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the insurance charges may have been excessive and even illegal, The <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, which recently reviewed a copy of the memo, reported in its Sunday editions. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said penalties could include heavy fines, forfeiture of interest collected and court-imposed damages. The Press said the Dec. 20 memo cautioned that attempts to correct the problem by refunding money to consumers might result in class-action lawsuits `` by calling attention to the situation.'' The insurance charges in question were imposed on an estimated 22,000 <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> auto loan customers, according to the newspaper. The memo was addressed to <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mangelsdorf </PERSON>, then an assistant vice president in charge of indirect lending. He now works for a bank in <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, N.Y. Neither <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Mangelsdorf </PERSON> would comment on the memo, The Press said. <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> said in a written response that after `` thoroughly'' exploring the issues raised in the memo, it had concluded its insurance program is in compliance with all laws and regulations. The Pittsburgh-based bank said it removed two of the charges cited by <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> from customers' statements earlier this year. The bank said that action reduced the customers' annual insurance premium. <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> it did so because the charges `` did not offer sufficiently substantial benefits to either our customers or the bank.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has ruled that the type of insurance referred to by <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> _ collateral protection insurance _ must provide benefits to both consumers and the bank. The insurance plan is called `` force-placed'' insurance. <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON>, like many lenders, requires new car owners to agree to buy physical damage insurance to protect the bank's collateral, which is the vehicle. Some banks self-insure on such losses, while others write off the losses. If a consumer allows his private insurance to expire, <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> obtains force-placed coverage and adds the insurance premium to the customer's car loan balance. The interest charged on the premium is the same as that charged on the auto loan, <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> said. Under this program, a customer's monthly car payment does not change, so the result is `` a balloon payment'' due when the loan matures, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. The interest on the premiums also accumulates until the loan matures. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON>'s program began as a means of cutting high loan losses but quickly became a money-maker for the bank. <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 884 million in 1987 and $ 65 million in 1988, but reported first-quarter profits this year of $ 77 million. <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said he recommended Feb. 7 that <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> rescind some of its premium charges and return money to customers. He said he was fired for insubordination two days later. <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON> disputed <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>'s account of his firing, calling him `` a disgruntled ex-employee.'' The bank told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> he was dismissed for `` appropriate business reasons'' unrelated to `` the product in question.'' `` That's nonsense,'' <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> replied. `` It was related directly to the product in question. My position was that if they -LRB- the legal department -RRB- deemed the product illegal _ which they did _ it should have been discontinued.''
